This past weekend was the Cote D'Azur, and it was AWESOME. We went to the beach and tanned and we ate really good food. The hotel was creepy, but it was the only bad part (I'm copying J West here: the hotel was called the Hotel Dante: "Abandon all hope, ye who enter here"). Saturday was Cannes, which was sandy and kind of like a beach at home. FYI: All the women who go topless are OLD, like 60's OLD. Poor Nikki saw some old man's nastiness when he decided he needed to take off and ring out his speedo. Eww. Sunday we went to the beach at Nice, which is rocky, but we had already decided we weren't going to lay out so no one had on bathing suits. J West wanted to go swimming in it bad, but couldn't so we picked up rocks and took pictures. Then we went to Monaco which I think had to be my favorite part. We were walking over to the Casino Monte Carlo when we stumbled across a Chanel. I swear I heard angels singing. (That's why I'm smiling so big in my new facebook picture.) Then we went by the casino and walked down the strip with Prada and Gucci while I drooled profusely. We took the bus out to the castle and the buses were running for free that day! I heart Monaco. So we got to see the Castle and the cathedral where Princess Grace and Prince Renier were married and are buried. It was awesome. That night after dinner J West put on her bathing suit and dragged us all down to the beach and she swam in the Mediterranean. It was funny. Then Jamie, Nikki, and I watched rollar bladers while J West called her Daddy and this poor guy was trying to impress Nikki (which was pretty much the case with every guy all weekend when Nikki's around) and kept knocking cones over and looking like a moron, so he moved the cones closer to us so she could see him being a jack ass up close. It was hilarious. Monday we came home and I was exhausted (the hotel beds were ASS) and grouchy, but it was an awesome weekend, Monte Carlo style. 

Yesterday Katrin and I had to go pick up our grades. It was nerve racking. But... we passed! YAY! So last night we went out to celebrate. We went to this crazy restaurant that's like old time-y Gaulle or something. Like you have pitchers and one cup each and they grill your meat in the room and it was weird, but the food was good. Then we went to the Pale for the last time and got pints and Katrin FINALLY stole a Guiness pint glass. She's been saying she would for the longest time now, so it was an exciting day. 

I also bought my second suitcase yesterday. It's MASSIVE. I did a practice pack and all of my stuff fit with a little room to spare, so I think everything will get home without having to involve the french postal system. I'm just ready to pack and get the apartment clean, or rather to get all the technical stuff over with. I'm starting to get nervous about coming home, but I can't help but still be excited.

Today was the wine festival... and if anything can get me out of my room it's a promise of all you can taste wine for 3 euros. It's an awesome time of year. So you go into town and the festival covers a ton of space, and for 3 euros you get a cute little wine glass with which you can taste as much wine as you want. And you can use it for both days because the french drink on Sunday. I went with Katrin's friend Nathan (who doesn't like wine at all), Katrin (who likes everything), Saara (who only like Rose), Emily (who like me is a huge red fan but I also enjoy a good dry white). We met this really funny old man who's North Korean but lives in France named Peter. I also met my soul mate. He was really fun to look at and he had bright blue eyes and he wore capris (they're popular here and according to me, men look hot in them) and if he's there tomorrow I'm going to take it as a sign that he needs to take me out sometime before I go home. Emily and I tasted his wine and you could taste just a little bit of cinnimon in it (Katrin said we were retarded, but I told her Emily's and my paletes were more adept to tasting the subtleties of red wine) and Emily said it tasted like Christmas. It was yummy and so was the guy serving it. I'll keep you posted on whether or not I'm going to elope and move to a french vineyard. Oh and P.S.... Saara tried to explain to two old men about the drinking age in America and they thought it was retarded so they didn't understand and it took her like 10 minutes to get the point across. Yay for America.

I got a pity talk. I'm 21 years old and I got a pity talk! I was online the other day and my friend who happens to be getting married this summer (a small civil ceremony, but she "already feels married inside her heart") gets online and after gushing about how she's "sickeningly and fabulously" in love she asks me if there's anyone in my life so I told her I was "sickeningly and fabulously" single, and then I got the pity talk. She told me, "He's out there Wendy. Maybe if you slowed down you'd be able to find him. You're always on the go, but he'll find you if you let him." Oh gag me. How does she know I'm not running from him (which I honestly probably am doing)?! Well then she has to bring up my ex, John and she asks me "so how are you doing with that?" People. I broke up with him, and it was a year and a half ago, but whenever I'm single she brings him up EVERY time I talk to her. It's obnoxious. So this time I decided maybe I needed to stop sugarcoating and I told her, "Darling, I was over John before we even broke up." So then she tried to convince me that I needed to date this guy who I've been friends with since the sixth grade. Doesn't she think I could have handled that on my own sometime in the past 10 years that I've known the kid?! Not to mention the fact that the guy is like a brother to me, and that's just sick. It's like it's terminal to be single. I understand that she is dellusionally happy being in a committed, marriage-bound relationship at 21, but to be completely honest, to me, serious relationships (especially those that seem to be marriage bound) are overrated and they tend to give me ulcers (see the quiz result below entitled "The Keys to Your Heart", particularly the section that relates to marriage). You know the episode of Sex and the City where Carrie breaks out in a rash and has panic attacks because she and Aidan get engaged? I have a sneaking suspicion I would go through something similar, considering my most serious relationship (which lasted a whopping year and a half) gave me ulcers. Literally. Love made me throw up blood. So if you're really my friend and really care about my well being try to keep me out of relationships so my stomach and the rest of me can rest easy.

I am on my last leg, so if this doesn't make any sense... tough. I love London. Just FYI... Friday: -Katrin and I left for London from the Tours airport (it's the only flight that leaves from it on Ryan Air... sketchy) and it wasn't a bad flight and we were both excited because we had managed to finish those damned papers for our civ professor who had agreed to meet us at 2 on monday when we get back. -We land in London and try to use the ATMs to get pounds and two different machines tell me that my card isn't valid or something along those lines and so I freak out (important information for appreciating this story: my bank just got bought out by SunTrust and they sent me a new bank card in the mail, but I'm not in Memphis, I'm in France, so I had told my Mom to call and make sure they didn't cut my card off)... to be continued. -We get into town by the little train. From there it was the handy dandy underground into the part of town we were staying to find the hotel (which was REALLY nice and we got a really good deal). -We go down Oxford Street to find something to eat and luck out and find a Pizza Hut! Awesome. We gorged ourselves on garlic bread and I got an individual meat lovers pizza (my favorite). -We went by Borders to get a little guide book and so I could pick up some things I've been wanting to read in English. -Back to the hotel via a little stand where I bought a phone card. Got to the hotel and I called home and made my Mom call the bank. I called her back 30 minutes later, and because she hadn't called the bank and because she had never verified my new card they had cancelled my old card. So I am in Europe with no means of getting cash. Woopee. -We try to relax and watch tv. We saw Windtalkers (crap) and Intolerable Cruelty (REALLY funny). Then we planned out the weekend and crashed. Saturday -We got to Westminster Abbey at the asscrack of dawn and saw the church, which was really cool. I hadn't been in since I was 13 so I liked it a lot. -Then we went to Buckingham Palace for the changing of the gaurd, but the place we were standing at didn't have a great view, and it started really late, so Katrin and I watched like 20 minutes of it and left. -We went to St. Paul's Catherdral which I had never seen the inside of. The crypt was neat... lots of famous people, but not as cool as Westminster. -The favorite part of my weekend... Shopping! I went to Top Shop and Urban Outfitters and loaded up on cute British things for my closet. It was awesome. -Dropped the goodies off at the hotel and rested a bit. -We went to Piccadilly Circus and walked down to this Indian restaurant I LOVE over by all the theatres. The exact same waiters were working as were working the 500,000,000 times I went there this summer. They had changed the table clothes from coral to lavendar however. -Went out to see the lights on Piccadilly and oooh and ahhh. It was fun. -Bed time... Sunday -Also an early morning, so we ended up getting to Madame Tussaud's Wax Museum at 9:30 (which is ungawdly in my opinion). It was fun though. We got goofy pictures with different people and it was fun. It was weird though, because now (as oppossed to when I was 13) your tour winds up at this planatarium place where they show a rinky dinky thing on stars and the vastness of the universe and blah, blah, blah... It was dull, but the only stupid part. -We walked down to Hyde Park via a Starbucks and an ATM for Katrin to go to Speaker's Corner. It was hilarious. Some man was RANTING about religion and about how women don't need to try to be men because men have enough problems as it is. This other guy was wearing a sign that said something to the effect of "Listen to me. I am very clever. I know everything. Blah, blah, blah..." -From Hyde Park we caught one of those open bus tours and took it around to see all the sights. It was "V.E. Day" to celebrate the end of WWII so Trafalgar Square was all set up for some outdoor concert thing and random parades of vetrans would march by. It was neat. -We jumped off the tour at the Tower of London and got a full english breakfast for lunch (eggs, toast, sausage, ham, fried tomato, beans) before going inside. We saw Bloddy Tower and the place where Ann Boleyn was beheaded and the Royal jewels. It was fun. We took a picture in front of one of those funny little gaurds and when I zoomed in on the guy he's sticking out his tongue in the picture! Before that his buddy who had just gotten off duty walked by and made a face at him and he laughed so I knew he wasn't a really serious kind of a gaurd, but I mean really! -We decided to take the boat to get back into town since it was covered on our bus ticket. The guide was hillarious. It was fun. -We got back on the bus from where the boat dropped us off and took it around to where we had started the tour. -We went over to this movie theatre we had seen to see what was playing and The Wedding Date was starting in 20 minutes so we went in and saw it. It was so cute! We had been wanting to see it and it worked out perfectly (just like In Good Company when we were in Dublin). -We walked down to Hard Rock and got dinner. We were both ass out tired and I thought Katrin was going to fall asleep in her Tupelo Tenders. -We dragged ass back to the hotel where we called our Mommies to say Happy Mothers Day. We watched a countdown of the top 100 number one singles of all time (we caught the top 20) and I decided that Moby, Sinead O'Connor, and Yoko Ono are evil and need to take a long walk off a short pier. FYI... Monday -Got up at 5:30 and showered and checked out and walked to the underground. Went back to the airport and check in for our flight and I did some more book shopping. What can I say... I'm a nerd. -Flew home and ran to the rooms to see where our civ professor wanted us to meet her since she had said in an e-mail that she would be giving an exam on Monday when I asked if we could meet her Monday at 2pm. Apparently something got lost in communication and she had sent an e-mail after we had already left for London saying that if we're going to be here on Monday to come take the exam like everyone else, but unfortunately (and we had already told her this when we e-mailed her last week and when we talked to her on Wednesday) we were in the air when the others took the exam. So we went out there and couldn't find her and this nice lady offered to put our papers in her box so we scribbled a note on the envelope and came back and wrote her an e-mail and now are worrying about whether or not she's going to accept the final assignment she gave us. What an f'ing idiot. I'm pissed and stressed out and seriously considering alcoholism. Wish me luck.
